aws::graph::propositions: # Cessna 310L Aircraft Accident at Tampa, Florida on August 21, 2019
A Cessna 310L aircraft with registration N2299F was substantially damaged in an accident near Tampa, Florida on August 21, 2019.
The accident occurred at approximately 1235 eastern daylight time.
The commercial pilot was not injured in the accident.
The aircraft was operated as a Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 personal flight.
The defining event of the accident was a system/component malfunction/failure (non-power).
The accident occurred during approach and landing phases.
The right main landing gear would not indicate down and locked during landing approach.
The pilot "wiggled" the light for the right main landing gear.
The pilot changed the light bulb for the right main landing gear indicator.
Despite the pilot's actions, the right main landing gear did not indicate down and locked.
The pilot continued the approach and landed.
During the landing roll, the right main landing gear began to collapse.
The pilot aborted the first landing and climbed to altitude.
At altitude, the pilot cycled the landing gear.
The pilot tried to extend the right main landing gear using the emergency gear extension procedure multiple times.
The pilot attempted abrupt maneuvers to get the right main landing gear down and locked.
The pilot was unable to get the right main landing gear down and locked.
The pilot attempted a second landing with the same results.
After the aborted second landing, the pilot contacted air traffic control.
The pilot declared an emergency.
The pilot diverted to a tower-controlled airport.
The pilot performed one low pass of the air traffic control tower.
The pilot performed one fly-by of the air traffic control tower.
The tower controller told the pilot that the right main landing gear appeared to be down.
The pilot returned for landing.
During the third landing attempt, the pilot again felt the right main landing gear was collapsing.
The pilot aborted the third landing attempt.
The pilot informed the tower controller that he would land gear-up.
The pilot subsequently performed a gear-up landing.
The pilot/operator reported that the damage to the aircraft was substantial.
During recovery of the airplane, airport maintenance personnel were unable to lock the right main landing gear using the emergency gear extension system.
Airport maintenance personnel were able to manually push the gear over-center and brace it.
Airport maintenance personnel secured the nose and left main landing gear over-center with heavy tie wraps.
Airport maintenance personnel towed the airplane to the ramp.

text:
# Factual Information

## History of Flight

| Approach | Sys/Comp malf/fail (non-power) (Defining event) |
| --- | --- |
| Approach-VFR pattern final | Miscellaneous/other |
| Approach-VFR go-around | Miscellaneous/other |
| Landing | Landing gear not configured |

On August 21, 2019, about 1235 eastern daylight time, a Cessna 310L, N2299F, was substantially damaged when it was involved in an accident near Tampa, Florida. The commercial pilot was not injured. The airplane was operated as a Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 personal flight.

The pilot stated that, while on landing approach, the right main landing gear would not indicate down and locked. He "wiggled" the light for the right main landing gear and changed the light bulb, but the right main landing gear did not indicate down and locked. He continued the approach and landed, but during the landing roll, the right main landing gear began to collapse. He aborted the landing and climbed to altitude, where he cycled the landing gear and tried to extend the right main landing gear using the emergency gear extension procedure multiple times. He also attempted abrupt maneuvers but was unable to get the right main landing gear down and locked. He then attempted a second landing, with the same results.

After the aborted second landing, he contacted air traffic control, declared an emergency, and diverted to a tower-controlled airport. He performed one low pass and one fly-by of the air traffic control tower and was told that the right main landing gear appeared to be down. He returned for landing and, during landing, again felt the right main landing gear was collapsing. He aborted the landing then informed the tower controller that he would land gear-up. He subsequently performed a gear-up landing. The pilot/operator subsequently reported that the damage to the aircraft was substantial.

During recovery of the airplane, airport maintenance personnel were unable to lock the right main landing gear using the emergency gear extension system but were able to manually push the gear over-center and brace it. They also secured the nose and left main landing gear over-center with heavy tie wraps and towed the airplane to the ramp.
